<div xmlns:oreatom="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/atom/" xmlns:ore="http://www.openarchives.org/ore/terms/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" class="item-summary-view-metadata">
<h1>Play-based interview methods for exploring young children’s perspectives on inclusion</h1>
<p class="author-item-view">
<a href="/xmlui/browse?value=Koller, Donna&amp;type=author&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;">Koller, Donna</a>
</p>
<h2>Citation</h2>Koller, D., &amp; San Juan, V. (2014). Play-based interview methods for exploring young children’s perspectives on inclusion. International Journal of Qualitative Studies in Education. Published online. DOI: 10.1080/09518398.2014.916434 <a href="http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/09518398.2014.916434#.U58QjSguItg">(link to study)
            							</a>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Insights</h2>
<div>
<p>When researchers use play-based research methods it allows children to discuss and identify complex issues related to inclusion of persons with disabilities in schools.</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Practice insights</h2>
<div>
<ul>
<li>Children with disabilities should be viewed not only as beneficiaries of but also as contributors to inclusive classrooms.&#13;<li />Further research is needed to find answers to the following questions: How do educators discuss inclusive practices with children? How do educators convey information about disabilities and dispel myths associating disability with sickness? What is the relationship between children’s perceptions of disability and the actions of adults around them? How do educators in inclusive settings use the term “helping”?</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Background/Rationale of the paper</h2>
<div>
<p>The researchers wanted to evaluate a play-based method of interviewing young children. The researchers used a play-based method to interview 12 typically developing children (children who did not need special education services). The child participants came from two child care settings that had children with disabilities in their programs. The researchers used dolls and pictures of children with special needs to engage the participants in the interview. Through the interview, the researchers tried to understand the following: how participants viewed disability; how they felt about children with disabilities being either included or segregated in school; and how they described their relationships with other children</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="simple-item-view-description">
<h2>Summary</h2>
<div>
<p>Most participants recognized disabilities and could describe features associated with having a physical disability such as using a wheelchair.  Most participants could also infer the presence of disabilities even when they had no obvious physical features. The participants had diverse opinions about the types of activities in which a person with a disability could participate.  Some participants felt that disabilities were barriers that prevented children from participating in physical activities. Other participants either ignored the disability while describing physical activities or noted ways in which children with disabilities had other unique skills that allowed them to participate in activities (such as using the mouth instead of arms to colour).&#13;<p />The participants knew about disabilities through their own experience of watching or interacting with persons with disabilities. Some children had learned about disabilities from their parents or through watching TV. A majority of the participants felt that children with disabilities should attend the same school as children without disabilities. The child participants felt that children without disabilities should help children with disabilities. While the participants shared that they would be willing to play with children with disabilities, they were not always able to describe ways in which they could play with them.  &#13;<p />Most participants did not have friendships with children with disabilities. When some participants did play with children with disabilities, they viewed this play differently from what they did with typical peers whom they considered their friends and also engaged in this play less often.</p>
</div>
</div>
<h2>Contact the Ryerson researcher(s)</h2>Donna Koller, Associate Professor, School of Early Childhood Studies <a href="&#10;            &#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;&#9;mailto:dkoller@ryerson.ca">(email)
            								</a>
